ce:section.ce:para:
The surface morphologies of the different coatings after immersion in SBF for 3, 7, and 14 days are given in Fig. 7
                        . After immersion in SBF for 3 days, there were micropores and some secondary apatite on the MAO coating (Fig. 7a), and many deep cracks on the PA and PL-0.02 g/mL coatings that were not completely degraded (Fig. 7b and c, respectively). Particularly, an irregular mud-like substance and the micropores of MAO can be easily observed. After 7 days of immersion, a number of white particles (secondary apatite) appeared on the Mg substrate due to the complete degradation of the MAO coating (Fig. 7e). However, the PA and PA-0.02 g/L coatings that were almost degraded still had many micropores of the MAO coating. Besides, the surfaces had fewer long cracks in contrast to the several short cracks seen after 3 days of immersion. These findings reveal that the PA and PA-0.02 g/L coatings have lower corrosion rates than does the MAO coating, which corresponds with the results from the EIS study. After 14 days of immersion, with the penetration of SBF, the MAO coating exhibited complete degradation on the surface (Fig. 7g–i). The surface of the MAO coating still had some mineralized particles with morphologies similar to those seen after immersion for 3 and 7 days. In the case of the PL-0.02 g/mL coating, the samples were fully covered with the apatite layer with some cracks due to drying in air. According to Cheon et al., surface defects such as pores, scratches and cracks with high surface energy are beneficial for HA nucleation and mineralization [4]. In the initial stages, the micropores produced by MAO and the small cracks on the PA and PL-0.02 g/mL coatings can provide sites for HA nucleation, but the concentration of OH− is a significant factor for HA mineralization. The alkali treatment and hydrolysis of PA radicals can form an interface with several OH− to accelerate HA mineralization. Therefore, it is concluded that the apatite-forming ability of the PL-0.02 g/mL coating in SBF was higher than that of the MAO coating. In addition, we also measured the rate of weight loss following immersion in SBF for 3, 7, and 14 days (Fig. 8
                        ). Fig. 8 showed that the weight loss in the PA and PL-0.02 g/mL coatings were lower than in the pure MAO coating on different days, revealing that the PL-0.02 g/mL coating forms more degradation products during immersion to counteract a part of the weight loss originating from pure degradation. The changes in the weight loss of the different coatings are also consistent with the findings from the EIS study.
